Communicated by:
ProMED

******
[3]
Date: Wed 2 Nov 2022
Source: Excelsior [in Spanish, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://www.excelsior.com.mx/nacional/aumentan-a-10-los-casos-de-meningitis-en-durango/1549954


The number of cases of aseptic meningitis increased to 10, so the Durango Health Secretariat coordinates protection actions in private hospitals. Irasema Kondo Padilla, Secretary of Health in the entity, stressed that actions, such as the IMSS, ISSSTE, Hospital 450, as well as SEDENA [Ministry of National Defense], are linked to respond to the health situation. During the meeting, the doctors representing the private hospitals presented their cases and the measures they are taking to contain the situation.

It was agreed to carry out a census of patients, and concentrate on those affected in the care module at Hospital 450, IMSS, and ISSSTE if they are beneficiaries. In case of requiring a surgical procedure, they will be referred to the Maternal and Child Hospital.

In the same way, it was agreed that the doctors representing the various hospitals, will have to report on possible cases on the page provided by COPRISED (Federal Commission for the Protection Against Sanitary Risks of Durango State; http://coprised.durango.gob.mx/; telephone 618 1 37 70 98) that present the characteristics according to the operational definition (female of reproductive age, subjected to a gynecologic-obstetric procedure through a blockade, starting in May 2022, and presenting intractable headache).

In addition, the public will be informed that the communication will be sent through the corresponding areas, urging them to review formal and official sources, in order to avoid false or erroneous news.

For his part, Carlos Maa Mares, representative of the private hospitals in Durango, announced that public and private hospitals are coordinated to carry out investigations and obtain results on the origin of cases of aseptic meningitis.

[Byline: Alma Gudino]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED


[Durango City (pop., 654 876 in 2015) is the capital and largest city of the Mexican state of Durango, located in northwestern Mexico (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Durango_City).

The latest news report above says that there are now a total of 42 patients, including 4 deaths, of "aseptic meningitis" apparently at several different hospitals in Durango City in the Durango State of Mexico, as a postoperative complication. 41 of the 42 affected patients are women who underwent some type(s) of surgeries that involved epidural anesthesia and use of a medication that has been seized by the investigating authorities. We are now told that the cause of the meningitis is a "fungus", but we are not told specifically which fungus is the cause or the means by which this infection occurred. Could it be due to fungal contaminant of a drug that was injected during an epidural procedure?

An epidural injection is delivery of a drug between the dura mater and the vertebral wall. Epidurals can be used during labor and childbirth, during and after some types of surgery, and to treat pain due to sciatica or a slipped disc. Fungal contamination of a drug administered epidurally caused the large, multistate invasive fungal infection outbreak associated with contaminated methylprednisolone injections in late 2012 and 2013 in the US (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4669562/) and another fungal meningitis outbreak in 2002 (ProMED post Fungal meningitis, contaminated drug - USA (03) 20021212.6046).

More information on this outbreak from knowledgeable sources would be appreciated. - Mod.ML

